BICEP
=================================
1. What is a Bicep File?
A Bicep file is an Infrastructure as Code (IaC) file used to define Azure resources.
- .bicep extension
- file name: main.bicep

Inside it you describe:
- Resource Group
- VNET
- VM
- AKS
- Storage Account
- Load Balancer
- NSG

--> Bicep compiles into ARM JSON before deployment.

2. What is written inside bicep file ?
- parameters     param vmName string                                       (input values)
- variable       var location = 'centralindia'                             (reusable values)
- Resources      resource storage 'Microsoft.Storage/storageAccounts@2023-05-01' = { name: 'mystorage'}
- output         output storageId string = storage.id                      (Return values) 
- Modules        module storage './storage.bicep' = { }
- Loops          resource vm 'Microsoft.Compute/virtualMachines@2023-03-01' = [for name in vmNames: {name: name}]
- Conditions     resource storage 'Microsoft.Storage/storageAccounts@2023-01-01' = if(createStorage) {}
- existing   // Reference existing resource

3. 5. What is What-If?
Before deployment, Azure can show what changes will happen.
No resources are created.
Dry-run feature.
Command:  az deployment group what-if -g dev-rg -f main.bicep

Possible output:
+ Create Storage Account
~ Modify VM Size
- Delete Old NSG

4. Convert bicep to ARM and ARM to bicep file

Convert into ARM using bicep
Command: az bicep build --file main.bicep          #main.json file produced

Convert into bicep using ARM
Command: az bicep decompile --file main.json         #main.bicep file produced

5. Azure commands

- az login                                                      # to login in azure
- az account show                                               # Show Subscription
- az account list -o table                                      # List Subscriptions
- az account set --subscription "SubscriptionName"              # Set Subscription
- az group create -n dev-rg -l centralindia                     # Create Resource Group
- az deployment group validate -g dev-rg -f main.bicep          # Validate Bicep
- az deployment group what-if -g dev-rg -f main.bicep           # What-if
- az deployment group create -g dev-rg -f main.bicep            # Deploy
- az bicep version                                              # Check bicep version

6. Real production flow
1. Write Bicep
2. Test locally
3. az bicep build
4. az deployment validate
5. az deployment what-if
6. Commit to Git
7. Pull Request
8. Azure DevOps Pipeline
9. Deploy
10. ARM Engine creates resources
11. Verify resources
12. Monitor

